General Solly Shoke (Netwerk24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; Flights to and from Cuba for SANDF chief General Solly Shoke, his wife, and three officials have cost the taxpayer almost R500&nbsp;000. &ldquo;In total, R442 643 was spent on plane tickets for the head of the South African Military and his delegation from 13 to 19 June 2016,&rdquo; Minister of Defence Nosiviwe Mapisa-Nqakula said in answer to a question from DA MP Kobus Marais,&nbsp;Netwerk24&nbsp;reported on Tuesday.&ldquo;Accommodation, car hire and other expenses were paid for by the hosts,&rdquo; the answer reads.In reply to a previous question by Marais about the purpose of the visit to Cuba, Mapisa-Nqakula said: &ldquo;It was a planned visit to his (Cuban) counterpart to strengthen ties between the two armies and to look at the progress of SANDF members studying in Cuba.&rdquo;The DA would still ask Mapisa-Nqakula which airline was used, what class they flew, what the itinerary was, and if the department paid for the flights in accordance with Treasury&rsquo;s savings measures.&ldquo;The spending is unacceptable considering that military equipment is in disrepair and that we are struggling to meet the requirements of peace agreements,&rdquo; Marais said in a statement.He said the DA would ask Auditor General Kimi Makwetu to investigate the matter.This was not the first time Shoke&rsquo;s travels had been questioned. In 2014, more than R100&nbsp;000 was spent on tickets to Malaysia for Shoke to attend a conference.Trade unions said at the time that Shoke refused to fly SAA or economy class &ldquo;because his backside is too large&rdquo;.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.